Array — the mutable, fixed-size, java-flavoured one.

An array is Scala's thin wrapper over a java array. It is mutable, fixed-size, and lives outside the immutable collections hierarchy. You use it when you need the exact memory layout a contiguous block of primitives gives you, or when you are talking to a java application programming interface that expects an array.

Three things to register. First, indexing uses parentheses, not square brackets. Square brackets in Scala always mean type parameters, never indices, so the array applied to i gives you the element at position i. Second, arrays are mutable — a val binds the array, but the contents can still change in place. This is exactly the gap notebook two hinted at: val locks the binding, not the value it points at. You can overwrite an element of a val-bound array, you just cannot rebind the val to a different array. Third, arrays cannot grow — they have a fixed length. If you need a resizable indexed sequence, use a vector for the immutable case, or a mutable array-buffer for the mutable case.

In practice you will see array in three places — low-level performance code, java interop, and Spark internals, because Spark stores partition data as primitive arrays for cache efficiency. There is also an updated method that returns a brand-new array with one position changed, when you want the immutable-style move instead of mutating in place.
